Package com.rb.nonbiz.collections

Class RBSortedSet<T>

java.lang.Object
com.rb.nonbiz.collections.RBSortedSet<T>
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Iterable<T>
public class RBSortedSet<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Iterable<T>
Similar to java.util.SortedSet. However, it is meant to be immutable. Always prefer RBSortedSet to a java.util.SortedSet, especially on an interface, but even inside a method's body, when possible. SortedSet implements the Set interface, which includes methods such as #add(), which we do not want. However, RBSortedSet intentionally has NO methods to modify it. That offers compile-time safety.
See Also:
for a class that helps you initialize a SortedRBSet.

    • emptyRBSortedSet

      public static <T> RBSortedSet<T> emptyRBSortedSet()
      There is no 0-item override for rbSortedSetOf. This is to force you to use emptyRBSortedSet, which is more explicit and makes reading tests easier. Likewise for singletonRBSortedSet(). Note that, since this class is immutable, we actually don't need a comparator for this empty object.
